To transform $A$ into $B,$ we need to make entries to the left of $a_{44}={\color{blue}\bbox[lightgray,2pt]{1}}$ equal to ${\color{red}0}.$
To do this, we can apply the following elementary column operations:
\begin{align*}
A
&=
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 1 & 6 & \color{blue}1 \\
8 & 1 & 2 & \color{blue}{5} \\
0 & 9 & -5 & \color{blue}4 \\
4 & 5 & 3 & \color{blue}\bbox[lightgray,2pt]{1}
\end{bmatrix}
&& \qquad
\begin{array}{l}
C_1:=C_1-4C_4
\end{array} \\[5pt]
&\sim
\begin{bmatrix}
-3 & 1 & 6 & \color{blue}1 \\
-12 & 1 & 2 & \color{blue}{5} \\
-16 & 9 & -5 & \color{blue}4 \\
\color{red}0 & 5 & 3 & \color{blue}\bbox[lightgray,2pt]{1}
\end{bmatrix}
&& \qquad
\begin{array}{l}
C_2:=C_2-5C_4
\end{array} \\[5pt]
&\sim
\begin{bmatrix}
-3 & -4 & 6 & \color{blue}1 \\
-12 & -24 & 2 & \color{blue}{5} \\
-16 & -11 & -5 & \color{blue}4 \\
\color{red}0 & \color{red}0 & 3 & \color{blue}\bbox[lightgray,2pt]{1}
\end{bmatrix}
&& \qquad
\begin{array}{l}
C_3:=C_3-3C_4
\end{array} \\[5pt]
&\sim
\begin{bmatrix}
-3 & -4 & 3 & \color{blue}1 \\
-12 & -24 & -13 & \color{blue}{5} \\
-16 & -11 & -17 & \color{blue}4 \\
\color{red}0 & \color{red}0 & \color{red}0 & \color{blue}\bbox[lightgray,2pt]{1}
\end{bmatrix} \\[5pt]
&= B.
\end{align*}
Therefore, the corresponding elementary column operations are
$\qquad$ $C_2:=C_2-5C_4\quad$ and $\quad C_3:=C_3-3C_4.$

The minor of $d_{33} = 7$ (third row, third column) is the determinant of the remaining entries when the column and row containing $7$ are removed:
\[
{D} =
\left\lbrack
\matrix {
3 & -2 & {\color{gray}\ast} \\
4 & -1 & {\color{gray}\ast} \\
{\color{gray}\ast} & {\color{gray}\ast} & \bbox[lightgray, 2pt]{\color{gray}7}
}
\right\rbrack
\]
So, the minor of $d_{33}=7$ is
\begin{align*}
\text{det}
\left[
\begin{array}{cc}
3 & -2 \\
4 & -1
\end{array}
\right]
&=
\left|
\begin{array}{cc}
3 & -2 \\
4 & -1
\end{array}
\right| \\[5pt]
&= 3 \cdot (-1) - (-2) \cdot 4 \\[5pt]
&= -3 - (-8) \\[5pt]
&= 5.
\end{align*}

First, we remove the third row and first column:
\[
{X} =
\left\lbrack
\matrix {
{\color{gray}\ast} & u & u^2 \\
{\color{gray}\ast} & w & w^2 \\
\bbox[lightgray, 2pt]{\color{gray}2} & {\color{gray}\ast}& {\color{gray}\ast}
}
\right\rbrack
\]
Next, we calculate the determinant:
\begin{align*}
\text{det}
\left[
\begin{array}{cc}
u & u^2 \\
w & w^2
\end{array}
\right]
&=
\left|\begin{array}{cc}
u & u^2 \\
w & w^2
\end{array}\right| \\[5pt]
&=
u \cdot w^2 - u^2 \cdot w \\[5pt]
&= uw^2 - wu^2\\[5pt]
&= uw(w-u)
\end{align*}

We multiply each entry of $Q$ by $\dfrac{1}{3},$ as follows:
\begin{align*}
\dfrac{1}{3} {Q}
&=
\dfrac{1}{3}
\left\lbrack
\matrix {
3 & 6 \\
0 & -9 \\
-3 & 0
}
\right\rbrack \\[5pt]
&=
\left\lbrack
\matrix {
\dfrac{1}{3} \cdot 3 & \dfrac{1}{3} \cdot 6 \\
\dfrac{1}{3} \cdot 0 & \dfrac{1}{3} \cdot (-9) \\
\dfrac{1}{3} \cdot (-3) & \dfrac{1}{3} \cdot 0
}
\right\rbrack \\[5pt]
&=
\left\lbrack
\matrix {
1 & 2 \\
0 & -3 \\
-1 & 0
}
\right\rbrack
\end{align*}

We multiply each entry of the matrix by $5$, as follows:
\begin{eqnarray}
\eqalign{
5
\left\lbrack
\matrix {
4 & 1 & -2
}
\right\rbrack
&=
\left\lbrack
